Assigning Tidal Covariates to Harbor Seal Haul-out

Josh M. London

    1. Alaska Fisheries Science Center, NOAA, Seattle, Washington, USA
      josh.london@noaa.gov
      orcid.org/0000-0002-3647-5046

Abstract

This document describes the process of assigning tidal covariates to Alaska harbor seal haul-out behavior derived from telemetry deployments. The data for haul-out behavior are pulled from the pephaulout R data package. The tidal calculations are determined via the XTide library which must be installed along with the tidextractr package (available on Github).

Introduction

library(pephaulout)
library(tidextractr)
library(tidyverse)
library(furrr)

percent timelines data w/ locations

the pephaulout package has haulout data from all species deployments within the PEP. Here, we’ll filter out just the “Pv” species. We will also create a tide_dt column that is set to the half-hour. We’ll use this for our tidal covariate prediction so it represents the mid-point of the hourly haul-out behavior.

data(tbl_percent_locs)

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::ungroup() %>% 
  dplyr::filter(species == "Pv") %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(speno, date_time) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(tide_dt = date_time + lubridate::dhours(0.5))

survey polygons w/ tide stations

Next, we need to associate all of the haul-out behavior locations with a survey polygon (and, thus, the assigned tidal station for that polygon).

We’ll get the survey polygons from the PEP PostgreSQL database.

library(DBI)
con <- dbConnect(RPostgres::Postgres(), 
                 host = Sys.getenv("PEP_IP"),
                 user = keyringr::get_kc_account("pgpep_londonj"),
                 password = keyringr::decrypt_kc_pw("pgpep_londonj"),
                 dbname = "pep")

The akpvpolys object is an sf object that represents each of the survey polygons. For those haul-out locations within a polygon, we can join easily using the st_intersets function. However, there are a significant number of locations outside of a polygon and we will want to link those to the nearest polygon. For this, we’ll rely on the nabor package. This package can only work with point data, so we’ll create a akpvpolys_cent object that represents the centroids of each survey polygon.

library(sf)
akpvpolys <- st_read(con, query = "SELECT * FROM surv_pv_cst.geo_polys where iliamna != 'Y'", 
                     geom_column = 'geom') %>% 
  sf::st_transform(3571)
akpvpolys_cent <- akpvpolys %>% sf::st_centroid()

poly_idx <- tbl_percent_locs %>%
  sf::st_intersects(akpvpolys) %>% 
  purrr::map_int(1,.default = NA)

akpvpolys <- akpvpolys %>% 
  sf::st_set_geometry(NULL)

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>%
  dplyr::bind_cols(akpvpolys[poly_idx,c("polyid","station")])

At this point, tbl_percent_locs has polyid and station assigned for any location that falls within a survey polygon (polygons associated with Iliamna Lake are not included). Of these, we will want to separate out glacial fjord habitats as those will not have tidal covariates associated with them. For the remaining locations, we’ll need to convert the point coordinates to a matrix and then relay on the nabor::knn() function to determine the nearest neighbor. This also provides us a distance calculation for the nearest neighbor.

glacial_polys <- st_read(con, query = "SELECT * FROM surv_pv_cst.geo_polys where glacier_name IS NOT NULL", 
                     geom_column = 'geom')
tbl_percent_glacial <- tbl_percent_locs %>% dplyr::filter(polyid %in% glacial_polys$polyid)
locs_na <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::filter(is.na(polyid)) %>% 
  sf::st_coordinates()

polys_mat <- akpvpolys_cent %>% 
  sf::st_coordinates()

library(nabor)

locs_poly_nn <- knn(data=polys_mat, query=locs_na, k = 1) %>% 
  purrr::map(as_tibble) %>% dplyr::bind_cols() %>% 
  dplyr::rename(poly_idx = V1, nn_dist = V11) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(polyid = akpvpolys_cent$polyid[poly_idx],
                station = akpvpolys_cent$station[poly_idx]) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-poly_idx)

locs_na <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::filter(is.na(polyid)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-c(polyid,station)) %>% 
  dplyr::bind_cols(locs_poly_nn)

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(polyid)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(nn_dist = 0) %>% 
  rbind(locs_na) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(speno,date_time)

calculate tidal covariates

At this point, we’re ready to do our tidal calculations. We’ll rely on the tidextractr package (available from jmlondon/tidextracr on GitHub). This package requires installation of the XTide command line tool.

We’re going to take advantage of parallel processing using the furrr package. To help with this, we’ll first nest our data.

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(speno,species,sex,age) %>% tidyr::nest()

Now, we’ll calcualte the tidal statistics we are interested in and bind those back into tbl_percent_locs. This could take a while, but we will speed things up a bit by using the furrr package for parallel processing.

create_tidestats <- function(tbl_data) {
  get_tide_height <- purrr::possibly(tidextractr::GetTideHeight, 
                                     otherwise = NA, quiet = FALSE)
  get_nearest <- purrr::possibly(tidextractr::GetNearestLow, 
                                 otherwise = NA, quiet = FALSE)
  
  tbl_data <- tbl_data %>%
    dplyr::mutate(
      tide_height = purrr::map2_dbl(tide_dt, station,
                                    ~ get_tide_height(.x, .y)),
      near_low = purrr::map2(tide_dt, station,
                             ~ get_nearest(.x, .y)),
      near_low_height = purrr::map_dbl(near_low, "height"),
      near_low_time = purrr::map(near_low, "time") %>%
        purrr::reduce(c)
    ) %>% 
    dplyr::filter(inherits(near_low_time,"POSIXct")) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(
      minutes_from_low = purrr::map2(tide_dt, near_low_time, 
                                     ~ difftime(.x, .y, units = "mins")) %>%
        as.numeric()
    ) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-(near_low))
}

plan(multiprocess)

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(data = furrr::future_map(data, create_tidestats))

The last step is to create our final tbl_percent_locs and tbl_percent_glacial data objects.

tbl_percent_locs <- tbl_percent_locs %>% tidyr::unnest()
usethis::use_data(tbl_percent_locs, overwrite = TRUE)

usethis::use_data(tbl_percent_glacial, overwrite = TRUE)
